trousers without it getting worn out or ugly. On the contrary. It becomes always better and more beautiful.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;From time to time, you touch it with your fingers, you take it out of your pocket and look at it all wet in the pouring rain or in the bath under the water or in a glass of water or in the sun or it shines at candle light when you turn and turn it about.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;And when night comes you feel the forms with your hands. At night, under the blanket when you are lonely or when you lie sick in a hospital bed between sterile walls, or when you die alone, I think it is beautiful to have something like this in your hand. You can warm yourself with it like with a hot stone. Or cool yourself like with a snow crystal or with a piece of blue ice. You can put the coins into fire or into water.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Here, all my worlds are concentrated and represented like a beautiful d&eacute;j&agrave;-vu of Eden.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;It is like a renaissance, like a resurrection in a new dimension.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;It is like entrance money into paradise.&lt;/div&gt;', id-126, typeOfObject-'TEXT', text_id-126, txt-'1.4.2.1', text_type-'', text_category-'', text_title_en-'LIKE ENTRANCE MONEY INTO PARADISE', text_title_ge-'SO ETWAS WIE EINTRITTSGELD INS PARADIES', text_keywords-'M&uuml;nze, coin, Paradies, paradise', text_date-'1978-10-01', text_summary_en-'', text_summary_ge-'', text_language-en, text_contents-'Copper, silver and gold are at least as noble as lapislazuli, ultramarine, linen, linseed-oil, polivinyl acetate, paper, eggs and grinded bricks. I designed the coins in the size of a soup plate; then the modeller forms it into plaster, and I continue to shape it until it is ready to be reduced to coin size. So the coins are not copies of my paintings. When I was first asked to make coins, I was very, very sceptical and almost against it. But this is always so when I am offered to work with a new material, if it is lithography, engraving, tapestry, silkscreen or glass. But afterwards, when I had my first results in hand, at first soup plate size in plaster, then coin size, I got more and more enthusiastic. Now, I carry the first coins always with me in my pocket as small works of art which I show to everybody. They are not money-coins in the usual sense because they are no legal currency. Maybe one could pay with my coins? That would be wonderful. My coins have no face and revers as usual but only a front side. On the revers there are embossed seals, stamps representing the hall-mark, the modeller&rsquo;s sign, the seal of the Austrian Mint, the editor&rsquo;s sign and the copyright sign, the year, the title and number of the work, the running edition number and my signature in gothic letters and in Japanese. Furthermore, the coins are not round but have irregular edges. The metal will be denaturated. The silver will be blackened with sulphur and will not look like new silver anymore. The copper will be darkened or greened by means of acid to get a verdigris aspect like the old Roman coins. The result is extraordinary. It is like things hundred or thousand years old, mysterious like ancient engravings, like very old rediscovered treasures. If you hold such a heavy peace of metal in your hand with all its light and shadow effects and the black and verdigris in the depths, you feel as if you walked into a wonderland. The plastic forms create a new dimension. The unreal of my shapes and forms becomes real to touch and feel even for the blind. Therefore, it becomes twice unreal because such shapes and forms must not be and can not be real. Otherwise we would already be in paradise. It is really incredible to be able to carry such a picture in the pocket of your trousers without it getting worn out or ugly. On the contrary. It becomes always better and more beautiful. From time to time, you touch it with your fingers, you take it out of your pocket and look at it all wet in the pouring rain or in the bath under the water or in a glass of water or in the sun or it shines at candle light when you turn and turn it about. And when night comes you feel the forms with your hands. At night, under the blanket when you are lonely or when you lie sick in a hospital bed between sterile walls, or when you die alone, I think it is beautiful to have something like this in your hand. You can warm yourself with it like with a hot stone. Or cool yourself like with a snow crystal or with a piece of blue ice. You can put the coins into fire or into water. Here, all my worlds are concentrated and represented like a beautiful d&eacute;j&agrave;-vu of Eden. It is like a renaissance, like a resurrection in a new dimension. It is like entrance money into paradise. ', text_contents_ge-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Kupfer, Silber, Gold sind zumindest genauso edel wie Ultramarin, Leinen, Polivinylacetat-Leim, Lein&amp;ouml;l, Eier und zerriebene Ziegel.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Die M&amp;uuml;nzen entwerfe ich pers&amp;ouml;nlich und arbeite eigenh&amp;auml;ndig an der Gipsform weiter, nachdem der Modelleur die Form in Tellergr&amp;ouml;&amp;szlig;e vorgestaltet hat. Es sind also keine Kopien von Bildern.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Als ich gebeten wurde, M&amp;uuml;nzen zu entwerfen, war ich sehr, sehr skeptisch und fast dagegen. Das ist aber immer so, wenn man mir ein neues Material zum Arbeiten anbietet, sei es Kupferstich, Litho, Gobelin, Seidensieb oder Glas.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Dann jedoch, als ich die ersten Resultate in Tellergr&amp;ouml;&amp;szlig;e in Gips, dann in M&amp;uuml;nzgr&amp;ouml;&amp;szlig;e in der Hand hatte, war ich mehr und mehr begeistert. Jetzt trage ich die ersten M&amp;uuml;nzen st&amp;auml;ndig bei mir im Sack herum als kleine Kunstwerke, die ich allen zeige.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Es sind keine M&amp;uuml;nzen im &amp;uuml;blichen Sinn, denn es ist kein Zahlungsmittel. Aber vielleicht kann man doch mit meinen M&amp;uuml;nzen zahlen? Das w&amp;auml;re wunderbar.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Die M&amp;uuml;nzen haben keinen Kopf und Adler, also nur eine Vorderseite. Hinten sind nur Stempel des Feingehaltes, Zeichen des Modelleurs, Jahr, Zeichen des &amp;Ouml;sterreichischen M&amp;uuml;nzamtes, des Herausgebers, das Copyrightzeichen, Titel und Oeuvrenummer, fortlaufende Auflagennummer und meine Signatur in Kurrentschrift und in Japanisch.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Au&amp;szlig;erdem sind die M&amp;uuml;nzen nicht rund, sondern haben einen unregelm&amp;auml;&amp;szlig;igen Rand. Und das Metall wird denaturiert. Silber wird schwarz und schaut nicht wie Silber aus. Kupfer wird dunkel oder gr&amp;uuml;nspangr&amp;uuml;n und wird wie alte r&amp;ouml;mische M&amp;uuml;nzen aussehen. &amp;Uuml;berhaupt ist das Resultat verbl&amp;uuml;ffend, so wie Werke aus dem vorigen Jahrhundert oder Jahrtausend, und so geheimnisvoll wie alte Stiche, wie alte, wiedergefundene Sch&amp;auml;tze.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Wenn man so ein St&amp;uuml;ck Metall so schwer in der Hand hat mit seinen Licht- und Schattenwirkungen und den Schw&amp;auml;rzungen und Gr&amp;uuml;nungen in den Tiefen, glaubt man, in ein Wunderland zu schreiten.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Die Plastizit&amp;auml;t erzeugt eine neue Dimension. Das Irreale meiner Formenwelt wird real, abtastbar, f&amp;uuml;hlbar, auch f&amp;uuml;r Blinde, und daher doppelt irreal, weil es solche Formen real nicht geben darf, nicht geben kann auf Erden, oder wir w&amp;auml;ren schon im Paradies. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Es ist wirklich unglaublich, so ein Bild im Hosensack zu tragen, ohne da&amp;szlig; es sich abnutzt, und dabei immer besser wird. Ab und zu f&amp;uuml;hlt man danach, zieht es aus der Tasche oder dem Portemonnaie und betrachtet es, na&amp;szlig; in str&amp;ouml;mendem Regen oder im Bad unter Wasser, im Wasserglas oder in der Sonne, oder es blitzt, wenn man es im Kerzenlicht hin- und herdreht.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Und wenn es Nacht ist, ertastet man die Formen mit den Fingern. Im Bett nachts unter der Decke, wenn man einsam ist oder wenn man krank im Spitalbett zwischen sterilen W&amp;auml;nden liegt, oder wenn man alleine stirbt, glaube ich, ist es sch&amp;ouml;n, so etwas in H&amp;auml;nden zu haben. Man kann sich daran w&amp;auml;rmen wie an einem hei&amp;szlig;en Stein. Oder k&amp;uuml;hlen wie an einem Schneekristall oder einem St&amp;uuml;ck aus blauem Eis. Man kann es ins Feuer legen oder ins Wasser.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Alle meine Welten sind hier konzentriert und schemenhaft zugleich vertreten, so wie eine Wiedergeburt, eine Wiederauferstehung in einer neuen Dimension.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Es ist so etwas wie Eintrittsgeld ins Paradies.&lt;/p&gt;', text_occasion_en-'&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; font-family: &#039;Times New Roman&#039;;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; font-family: &#039;Times New Roman&#039;;&quot;&gt;Written in Kaurinui on &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; font-family: &#039;Times New Roman&#039;;&quot;&gt;1 October 1978 &lt;/span&gt;on occasion of his designs for coins.&lt;/span&gt;', text_occasion_ge-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Verfa&amp;szlig;t anl&amp;auml;&amp;szlig;lich der Entw&amp;uuml;rfe f&amp;uuml;r M&amp;uuml;nzen 1978.&lt;/p&gt;', text_published_en-'&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Hundertwasser Coin catalogue, Gruener Janura AG: Glarus/Switzerland, 1978, pp. 3-6&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Schurian, Walter (ed.): Hundertwasser &amp;ndash; Sch&amp;ouml;ne Wege, Gedanken &amp;uuml;ber Kunst und Leben. (Beautiful Paths &amp;ndash; Thoughts on Art and Life) Deutscher Taschenbuch Verlag (dtv): Munich, 1983, pp. 80-82 and ed. 2004 (Langen M&amp;uuml;ller Verlag, Munich), pp. 97-98 (German)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Schmied, Wieland (ed.): Hundertwasser 1928&amp;ndash;2000, Catalogue Raisonn&amp;eacute;.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Vol. II: F&amp;uuml;rst, Andrea Christa: Catalogue Raisonn&amp;eacute;. Taschen: Cologne, 2002, pp. 1022-1023 (German and English)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;', text_published_ge-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Katalog zu den Hundertwasser M&amp;uuml;nzen, Gruener Janura AG: Glarus/Schweiz, 1978, S. 10-15&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Schurian, Walter (Hg.): Hundertwasser &amp;ndash; Sch&amp;ouml;ne Wege, Gedanken &amp;uuml;ber Kunst und Leben. Deutscher Taschenbuch Verlag (dtv): M&amp;uuml;nchen 1983, S. 80-82 und Ausgabe 2004 (Langen M&amp;uuml;ller Verlag, M&amp;uuml;nchen), S. 97-98&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Schmied, Wieland (Hg.): Hundertwasser 1928&amp;ndash;2000, Catalogue Raisonn&amp;eacute; / Werkverzeichnis.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Vol. II: F&amp;uuml;rst, Andrea Christa: Catalogue Raisonn&amp;eacute; / Werkverzeichnis. Taschen: K&amp;ouml;ln 2002, S. 1022-1023 (Deutsch und Englisch)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;', text_author-'Hundertwasser', text_orig_lang-'', text_translator-'', text_source_en-'', text_source_ge-'', text_excerpt-'', text_origin-'']

%2###2010-2-16 7:4:6.58418###object###text###1.4.2.1###LIKE ENTRANCE MONEY INTO PARADISE

[text_contents_en-'&lt;div&gt;&lt;a onclick=&quot;return showBox(this);&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;/kb/edit?id=1.4.2.1&amp;amp;type=text&quot; class=&quot;thumb_image&quot;&gt;Edit&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;thumb_image&quot; href=&quot;/kb/edit?id=1.4.2.1&amp;amp;type=text&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; onclick=&quot;return showBox(this);&quot;&gt;Edit&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;thumb_image&quot; href=&quot;/kb/edit?id=1.4.2.1&amp;amp;type=text&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; onclick=&quot;return showBox(this);&quot;&gt;Edit&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Copper, silver and gold are at least as noble as lapislazuli, ultramarine, linen, linseed-oil, polivinyl acetate, paper, eggs and grinded bricks. I designed the coins in the size of a soup plate; then the modeller forms it into plaster, and I continue to shape it until it is ready to be reduced to coin size. So the coins are not copies of my paintings. &lt;span id=&quot;hlS-80&quot; class=&quot;hw-highlight&quot; style=&quot;cursor: pointer;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;hlS-80&quot; class=&quot;hw-highlight&quot; style=&quot;cursor: pointer;&quot;&gt;80&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt;When I was first asked to make coins, I was very, very sceptical and almost against it. But this is always so when I am offered to work with a new material, if it is lithography, engraving, tapestry, silkscreen or glass.&lt;span id=&quot;hlE-80&quot; class=&quot;hw-highlight&quot; style=&quot;cursor: pointer;&quot;&gt;&amp;lt;&amp;lt;&amp;lt;80 &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;But afterwards, when I had my first results in hand, at first soup plate size in plaster, then coin size, I got more and more enthusiastic.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Now, I carry the first coins always with me in my pocket as small works of art which I show to everybody. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;They are not money-coins in the usual sense because they are no legal currency. Maybe one could pay with my coins? That would be wonderful. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;My coins have no face and revers as usual but only a front side. On the revers there are embossed seals, stamps representing the hall-mark, the modeller&rsquo;s sign, the seal of the Austrian Mint, the editor&rsquo;s sign and the copyright sign, the year, the title and number of the work, the running edition number and my signature in gothic letters and in Japanese. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Furthermore, the coins are not round but have irregular edges. The metal will be denaturated. The silver will be blackened with sulphur and will not look like new silver anymore. The copper will be darkened or greened by means of acid to get a verdigris aspect like the old Roman coins. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The result is extraordinary. It is like things hundred or thousand years old, mysterious like ancient engravings, like very old rediscovered treasures.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;If you hold such a heavy peace of metal in your hand with all its light and shadow effects and the black and verdigris in the depths, you feel as if you walked into a wonderland. The plastic forms create a new dimension. The unreal of my shapes and forms becomes real to touch and feel even for the blind. Therefore, it becomes twice unreal because such shapes and forms must not be and can not be real. Otherwise we would already be in paradise.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;It is really incredible to be able to carry such a picture in the pocket of your trousers without it getting worn out or ugly. On the contrary. It becomes always better and more beautiful. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;From time to time, you touch it with your fingers, you take it out of your pocket and look at it all wet in the pouring rain or in the bath under the water or in a glass of water or in the sun or it shines at candle light when you turn and turn it about. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;And when night comes you feel the forms with your hands. At night, under the blanket when you are lonely or when you lie sick in a hospital bed between sterile walls, or when you die alone, I think it is beautiful to have something like this in your hand. You can warm yourself with it like with a hot stone. Or cool yourself like with a snow crystal or with a piece of blue ice. You can put the coins into fire or into water. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Here, all my worlds are concentrated and represented like a beautiful d&eacute;j&agrave;-vu of Eden. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;It is like a renaissance, like a resurrection in a new dimension. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;It is like entrance money into paradise.&lt;/div&gt;', id-126, typeOfObject-'TEXT', text_id-126, txt-'1.4.2.1', text_type-'', text_category-'', text_title_en-'LIKE ENTRANCE MONEY INTO PARADISE', text_title_ge-'SO ETWAS WIE EINTRITTSGELD INS PARADIES', text_keywords-'M&uuml;nze, coin, Paradies, paradise', text_date-'1978-10-01', text_summary_en-'', text_summary_ge-'', text_language-en, text_contents-'Copper, silver and gold are at least as noble as lapislazuli, ultramarine, linen, linseed-oil, polivinyl acetate, paper, eggs and grinded bricks. I designed the coins in the size of a soup plate; then the modeller forms it into plaster, and I continue to shape it until it is ready to be reduced to coin size. So the coins are not copies of my paintings. When I was first asked to make coins, I was very, very sceptical and almost against it. But this is always so when I am offered to work with a new material, if it is lithography, engraving, tapestry, silkscreen or glass. But afterwards, when I had my first results in hand, at first soup plate size in plaster, then coin size, I got more and more enthusiastic. Now, I carry the first coins always with me in my pocket as small works of art which I show to everybody. They are not money-coins in the usual sense because they are no legal currency. Maybe one could pay with my coins? That would be wonderful. My coins have no face and revers as usual but only a front side. On the revers there are embossed seals, stamps representing the hall-mark, the modeller&rsquo;s sign, the seal of the Austrian Mint, the editor&rsquo;s sign and the copyright sign, the year, the title and number of the work, the running edition number and my signature in gothic letters and in Japanese. Furthermore, the coins are not round but have irregular edges. The metal will be denaturated. The silver will be blackened with sulphur and will not look like new silver anymore. The copper will be darkened or greened by means of acid to get a verdigris aspect like the old Roman coins. The result is extraordinary. It is like things hundred or thousand years old, mysterious like ancient engravings, like very old rediscovered treasures. If you hold such a heavy peace of metal in your hand with all its light and shadow effects and the black and verdigris in the depths, you feel as if you walked into a wonderland. The plastic forms create a new dimension. The unreal of my shapes and forms becomes real to touch and feel even for the blind. Therefore, it becomes twice unreal because such shapes and forms must not be and can not be real. Otherwise we would already be in paradise. It is really incredible to be able to carry such a picture in the pocket of your trousers without it getting worn out or ugly. On the contrary. It becomes always better and more beautiful. From time to time, you touch it with your fingers, you take it out of your pocket and look at it all wet in the pouring rain or in the bath under the water or in a glass of water or in the sun or it shines at candle light when you turn and turn it about. And when night comes you feel the forms with your hands. At night, under the blanket when you are lonely or when you lie sick in a hospital bed between sterile walls, or when you die alone, I think it is beautiful to have something like this in your hand. You can warm yourself with it like with a hot stone. Or cool yourself like with a snow crystal or with a piece of blue ice. You can put the coins into fire or into water. Here, all my worlds are concentrated and represented like a beautiful d&eacute;j&agrave;-vu of Eden. It is like a renaissance, like a resurrection in a new dimension. It is like entrance money into paradise. ', text_contents_ge-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Kupfer, Silber, Gold sind zumindest genauso edel wie Ultramarin, Leinen, Polivinylacetat-Leim, Lein&amp;ouml;l, Eier und zerriebene Ziegel.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Die M&amp;uuml;nzen entwerfe ich pers&amp;ouml;nlich und arbeite eigenh&amp;auml;ndig an der Gipsform weiter, nachdem der Modelleur die Form in Tellergr&amp;ouml;&amp;szlig;e vorgestaltet hat. Es sind also keine Kopien von Bildern.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Als ich gebeten wurde, M&amp;uuml;nzen zu entwerfen, war ich sehr, sehr skeptisch und fast dagegen. Das ist aber immer so, wenn man mir ein neues Material zum Arbeiten anbietet, sei es Kupferstich, Litho, Gobelin, Seidensieb oder Glas.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Dann jedoch, als ich die ersten Resultate in Tellergr&amp;ouml;&amp;szlig;e in Gips, dann in M&amp;uuml;nzgr&amp;ouml;&amp;szlig;e in der Hand hatte, war ich mehr und mehr begeistert. Jetzt trage ich die ersten M&amp;uuml;nzen st&amp;auml;ndig bei mir im Sack herum als kleine Kunstwerke, die ich allen zeige.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Es sind keine M&amp;uuml;nzen im &amp;uuml;blichen Sinn, denn es ist kein Zahlungsmittel. Aber vielleicht kann man doch mit meinen M&amp;uuml;nzen zahlen? Das w&amp;auml;re wunderbar.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Die M&amp;uuml;nzen haben keinen Kopf und Adler, also nur eine Vorderseite. Hinten sind nur Stempel des Feingehaltes, Zeichen des Modelleurs, Jahr, Zeichen des &amp;Ouml;sterreichischen M&amp;uuml;nzamtes, des Herausgebers, das Copyrightzeichen, Titel und Oeuvrenummer, fortlaufende Auflagennummer und meine Signatur in Kurrentschrift und in Japanisch.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Au&amp;szlig;erdem sind die M&amp;uuml;nzen nicht rund, sondern haben einen unregelm&amp;auml;&amp;szlig;igen Rand. Und das Metall wird denaturiert. Silber wird schwarz und schaut nicht wie Silber aus. Kupfer wird dunkel oder gr&amp;uuml;nspangr&amp;uuml;n und wird wie alte r&amp;ouml;mische M&amp;uuml;nzen aussehen. &amp;Uuml;berhaupt ist das Resultat verbl&amp;uuml;ffend, so wie Werke aus dem vorigen Jahrhundert oder Jahrtausend, und so geheimnisvoll wie alte Stiche, wie alte, wiedergefundene Sch&amp;auml;tze.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Wenn man so ein St&amp;uuml;ck Metall so schwer in der Hand hat mit seinen Licht- und Schattenwirkungen und den Schw&amp;auml;rzungen und Gr&amp;uuml;nungen in den Tiefen, glaubt man, in ein Wunderland zu schreiten.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span roman=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Die Plastizit&amp;auml;t erzeugt eine neue Dimension. Das Irreale meiner Formenwelt wird real, abtastbar, f&amp;uuml;hlbar, auch f&amp;uuml;r Blinde, und daher doppelt irreal, weil es solche Formen real nicht geben darf, nicht geben kann auf Erden, oder wir w&amp;auml;ren schon im Paradies. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Es ist wirklich unglaublich, so ein Bild im Hosensack zu tragen, ohne da&amp;szlig; es sich abnutzt, und dabei immer besser wird. Ab und zu f&amp;uuml;hlt man danach, zieht es aus der Tasche oder dem Portemonnaie und betrachtet es, na&amp;szlig; in str&amp;ouml;mendem Regen oder im Bad unter Wasser, im Wasserglas oder in der Sonne, oder es blitzt, wenn man es im Kerzenlicht hin- und herdreht.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Und wenn es Nacht ist, ertastet man die Formen mit den Fingern. Im Bett nachts unter der Decke, wenn man einsam ist oder wenn man krank im Spitalbett zwischen sterilen W&amp;auml;nden liegt, oder wenn man alleine stirbt, glaube ich, ist es sch&amp;ouml;n, so etwas in H&amp;auml;nden zu haben. Man kann sich daran w&amp;auml;rmen wie an einem hei&amp;szlig;en Stein. Oder k&amp;uuml;hlen wie an einem Schneekristall oder einem St&amp;uuml;ck aus blauem Eis. Man kann es ins Feuer legen oder ins Wasser.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Alle meine Welten sind hier konzentriert und schemenhaft zugleich vertreten, so wie eine Wiedergeburt, eine Wiederauferstehung in einer neuen Dimension.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Es ist so etwas wie Eintrittsgeld ins Paradies.&lt;/p&gt;', text_occasion_en-'&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; font-family: &#039;Times New Roman&#039;;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; font-family: &#039;Times New Roman&#039;;&quot;&gt;Written in Kaurinui on &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; font-family: &#039;Times New Roman&#039;;&quot;&gt;1 October 1978 &lt;/span&gt;on occasion of his designs for coins.&lt;/span&gt;', text_occasion_ge-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Verfa&amp;szlig;t anl&amp;auml;&amp;szlig;lich der Entw&amp;uuml;rfe f&amp;uuml;r M&amp;uuml;nzen 1978.&lt;/p&gt;', text_published_en-'&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Hundertwasser Coin catalogue, Gruener Janura AG: Glarus/Switzerland, 1978, pp. 3-6&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Schurian, Walter (ed.): Hundertwasser &amp;ndash; Sch&amp;ouml;ne Wege, Gedanken &amp;uuml;ber Kunst und Leben. (Beautiful Paths &amp;ndash; Thoughts on Art and Life) Deutscher Taschenbuch Verlag (dtv): Munich, 1983, pp. 80-82 and ed. 2004 (Langen M&amp;uuml;ller Verlag, Munich), pp. 97-98 (German)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Schmied, Wieland (ed.): Hundertwasser 1928&amp;ndash;2000, Catalogue Raisonn&amp;eacute;.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Vol. II: F&amp;uuml;rst, Andrea Christa: Catalogue Raisonn&amp;eacute;. Taschen: Cologne, 2002, pp. 1022-1023 (German and English)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;', text_published_ge-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Katalog zu den Hundertwasser M&amp;uuml;nzen, Gruener Janura AG: Glarus/Schweiz, 1978, S. 10-15&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Schurian, Walter (Hg.): Hundertwasser &amp;ndash; Sch&amp;ouml;ne Wege, Gedanken &amp;uuml;ber Kunst und Leben. Deutscher Taschenbuch Verlag (dtv): M&amp;uuml;nchen 1983, S. 80-82 und Ausgabe 2004 (Langen M&amp;uuml;ller Verlag, M&amp;uuml;nchen), S. 97-98&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Schmied, Wieland (Hg.): Hundertwasser 1928&amp;ndash;2000, Catalogue Raisonn&amp;eacute; / Werkverzeichnis.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Vol. II: F&amp;uuml;rst, Andrea Christa: Catalogue Raisonn&amp;eacute; / Werkverzeichnis. Taschen: K&amp;ouml;ln 2002, S. 1022-1023 (Deutsch und Englisch)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;', text_author-'Hundertwasser', text_orig_lang-'', text_translator-'', text_source_en-'', text_source_ge-'', text_excerpt-'', text_origin-'']

%2###2010-2-16 7:16:6.54714###object###text###1.4.2.1###LIKE ENTRANCE MONEY INTO PARADISE

[text_contents_en-'&lt;div&gt;&lt;a onclick=&quot;return showBox(this);&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;/kb/edit?id=1.4.2.1&amp;amp;type=text&quot; class=&quot;thumb_image&quot;&gt;Edit&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;thumb_image&quot; href=&quot;/kb/edit?id=1.4.2.1&amp;amp;type=text&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; onclick=&quot;return showBox(this);&quot;&gt;Edit&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;a onclick=&quot;return showBox(this);&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;/kb/edit?id=1.4.2.1&amp;amp;type=text&quot; class=&quot;thumb_image&quot;&gt;Edit&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;a onclick=&quot;return showBox(this);&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;/kb/edit?id=1.4.2.1&amp;amp;type=text&quot; class=&quot;thumb_image&quot;&gt;Edit&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Copper, silver and gold are at least as noble as lapislazuli, ultramarine, linen, linseed-oil, polivinyl acetate, paper, eggs and grinded bricks. I designed the coins in the size of a soup plate; then the modeller forms it into plaster, and I continue to shape it until it is ready to be reduced to coin size. So the coins are not copies of my paintings. &lt;span style=&quot;cursor: pointer;&quot; class=&quot;hw-highlight&quot; id=&quot;hlS-80&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;cursor: pointer;&quot; class=&quot;hw-highlight&quot; id=&quot;hlS-80&quot;&gt;80&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt;When I was first asked to make coins, I was very, very sceptical and almost against it. But this is always so when I am offered to work with a new material, if it is lithography, engraving, tapestry, silkscreen or glass.&lt;span style=&quot;cursor: pointer;&quot; class=&quot;hw-highlight&quot; id=&quot;hlE-80&quot;&gt;&amp;lt;&amp;lt;&amp;lt;80 &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;But afterwards, when I had my first results in hand, at first soup plate size in plaster, then coin size, I got more and more enthusiastic.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Now, I carry the first coins always with me in my pocket as small works of art which I show to everybody.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;They are not money-coins in the usual sense because they are no legal currency. Maybe one could pay with my coins? That would be wonderful.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;My coins have no face and revers as usual but only a front side. On the revers there are embossed seals, stamps representing the hall-mark, the modeller&rsquo;s sign, the seal of the Austrian Mint, the editor&rsquo;s sign and the copyright sign, the year, the title and number of the work, the running edition number and my signature in gothic letters and in Japanese.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Furthermore, the coins are not round but have irregular edges. The metal will be denaturated. The silver will be blackened with sulphur and will not look like new silver anymore. The copper will be darkened or greened by means of acid to get a verdigris aspect like the old Roman coins.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The result is extraordinary. It is like things hundred or thousand years old, mysterious like ancient engravings, like very old rediscovered treasures.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;cursor: pointer;&quot; class=&quot;hw-highlight&quot; id=&quot;hlS-156&quot;&gt; 156&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt;If you hold such a heavy piece of metal in your hand with all its light and shadow effects and the black and verdigris in the depths, you feel as if you walked into a wonderland. The plastic forms create a new dimension. The unreal of my shapes and forms becomes real to touch and feel even for the blind. Therefore, it becomes twice unreal because such shapes and forms must not be and can not be real. Otherwise we would already be in paradise.&lt;span style=&quot;cursor: pointer;&quot; class=&quot;hw-highlight&quot; id=&quot;hlE-156&quot;&gt;&amp;lt;&amp;lt;&amp;lt;156 &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;It is really incredible to be able to carry such a picture in the pocket of your trousers without it getting worn out or ugly. On the contrary. It becomes always better and more beautiful.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;From time to time, you touch it with your fingers, you take it out of your pocket and look at it all wet in the pouring rain or in the bath under the water or in a glass of water or in the sun or it shines at candle light when you turn and turn it about.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;And when night comes you feel the forms with your hands. At night, under the blanket when you are lonely or when you lie sick in a hospital bed between sterile walls, or when you die alone, I think it is beautiful to have something like this in your hand. You can warm yourself with it like with a hot stone. Or cool yourself like with a snow crystal or with a piece of blue ice. You can put the coins into fire or into water.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Here, all my worlds are concentrated and represented like a beautiful d&eacute;j&agrave;-vu of Eden.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;It is like a renaissance, like a resurrection in a new dimension.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;It is like entrance money into paradise.&lt;/div&gt;', id-126, typeOfObject-'TEXT', text_id-126, txt-'1.4.2.1', text_type-'', text_category-'', text_title_en-'LIKE ENTRANCE MONEY INTO PARADISE', text_title_ge-'SO ETWAS WIE EINTRITTSGELD INS PARADIES', text_keywords-'M&uuml;nze, coin, Paradies, paradise', text_date-'1978-10-01', text_summary_en-'', text_summary_ge-'', text_language-en, text_contents-'Copper, silver and gold are at least as noble as lapislazuli, ultramarine, linen, linseed-oil, polivinyl acetate, paper, eggs and grinded bricks. I designed the coins in the size of a soup plate; then the modeller forms it into plaster, and I continue to shape it until it is ready to be reduced to coin size. So the coins are not copies of my paintings. When I was first asked to make coins, I was very, very sceptical and almost against it. But this is always so when I am offered to work with a new material, if it is lithography, engraving, tapestry, silkscreen or glass. But afterwards, when I had my first results in hand, at first soup plate size in plaster, then coin size, I got more and more enthusiastic. Now, I carry the first coins always with me in my pocket as small works of art which I show to everybody. They are not money-coins in the usual sense because they are no legal currency. Maybe one could pay with my coins? That would be wonderful. My coins have no face and revers as usual but only a front side. On the revers there are embossed seals, stamps representing the hall-mark, the modeller&rsquo;s sign, the seal of the Austrian Mint, the editor&rsquo;s sign and the copyright sign, the year, the title and number of the work, the running edition number and my signature in gothic letters and in Japanese. Furthermore, the coins are not round but have irregular edges. The metal will be denaturated. The silver will be blackened with sulphur and will not look like new silver anymore. The copper will be darkened or greened by means of acid to get a verdigris aspect like the old Roman coins. The result is extraordinary. It is like things hundred or thousand years old, mysterious like ancient engravings, like very old rediscovered treasures. If you hold such a heavy peace of metal in your hand with all its light and shadow effects and the black and verdigris in the depths, you feel as if you walked into a wonderland. The plastic forms create a new dimension. The unreal of my shapes and forms becomes real to touch and feel even for the blind. Therefore, it becomes twice unreal because such shapes and forms must not be and can not be real. Otherwise we would already be in paradise. It is really incredible to be able to carry such a picture in the pocket of your trousers without it getting worn out or ugly. On the contrary. It becomes always better and more beautiful. From time to time, you touch it with your fingers, you take it out of your pocket and look at it all wet in the pouring rain or in the bath under the water or in a glass of water or in the sun or it shines at candle light when you turn and turn it about. And when night comes you feel the forms with your hands. At night, under the blanket when you are lonely or when you lie sick in a hospital bed between sterile walls, or when you die alone, I think it is beautiful to have something like this in your hand. You can warm yourself with it like with a hot stone. Or cool yourself like with a snow crystal or with a piece of blue ice. You can put the coins into fire or into water. Here, all my worlds are concentrated and represented like a beautiful d&eacute;j&agrave;-vu of Eden. It is like a renaissance, like a resurrection in a new dimension. It is like entrance money into paradise. ', text_contents_ge-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Kupfer, Silber, Gold sind zumindest genauso edel wie Ultramarin, Leinen, Polivinylacetat-Leim, Lein&amp;ouml;l, Eier und zerriebene Ziegel.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Die M&amp;uuml;nzen entwerfe ich pers&amp;ouml;nlich und arbeite eigenh&amp;auml;ndig an der Gipsform weiter, nachdem der Modelleur die Form in Tellergr&amp;ouml;&amp;szlig;e vorgestaltet hat. Es sind also keine Kopien von Bildern.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Als ich gebeten wurde, M&amp;uuml;nzen zu entwerfen, war ich sehr, sehr skeptisch und fast dagegen. Das ist aber immer so, wenn man mir ein neues Material zum Arbeiten anbietet, sei es Kupferstich, Litho, Gobelin, Seidensieb oder Glas.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Dann jedoch, als ich die ersten Resultate in Tellergr&amp;ouml;&amp;szlig;e in Gips, dann in M&amp;uuml;nzgr&amp;ouml;&amp;szlig;e in der Hand hatte, war ich mehr und mehr begeistert. Jetzt trage ich die ersten M&amp;uuml;nzen st&amp;auml;ndig bei mir im Sack herum als kleine Kunstwerke, die ich allen zeige.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Es sind keine M&amp;uuml;nzen im &amp;uuml;blichen Sinn, denn es ist kein Zahlungsmittel. Aber vielleicht kann man doch mit meinen M&amp;uuml;nzen zahlen? Das w&amp;auml;re wunderbar.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Die M&amp;uuml;nzen haben keinen Kopf und Adler, also nur eine Vorderseite. Hinten sind nur Stempel des Feingehaltes, Zeichen des Modelleurs, Jahr, Zeichen des &amp;Ouml;sterreichischen M&amp;uuml;nzamtes, des Herausgebers, das Copyrightzeichen, Titel und Oeuvrenummer, fortlaufende Auflagennummer und meine Signatur in Kurrentschrift und in Japanisch.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Au&amp;szlig;erdem sind die M&amp;uuml;nzen nicht rund, sondern haben einen unregelm&amp;auml;&amp;szlig;igen Rand. Und das Metall wird denaturiert. Silber wird schwarz und schaut nicht wie Silber aus. Kupfer wird dunkel oder gr&amp;uuml;nspangr&amp;uuml;n und wird wie alte r&amp;ouml;mische M&amp;uuml;nzen aussehen. &amp;Uuml;berhaupt ist das Resultat verbl&amp;uuml;ffend, so wie Werke aus dem vorigen Jahrhundert oder Jahrtausend, und so geheimnisvoll wie alte Stiche, wie alte, wiedergefundene Sch&amp;auml;tze.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Wenn man so ein St&amp;uuml;ck Metall so schwer in der Hand hat mit seinen Licht- und Schattenwirkungen und den Schw&amp;auml;rzungen und Gr&amp;uuml;nungen in den Tiefen, glaubt man, in ein Wunderland zu schreiten.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot; times=&quot;&quot; new=&quot;&quot; roman=&quot;&quot;&gt;Die Plastizit&amp;auml;t erzeugt eine neue Dimension. Das Irreale meiner Formenwelt wird real, abtastbar, f&amp;uuml;hlbar, auch f&amp;uuml;r Blinde, und daher doppelt irreal, weil es solche Formen real nicht geben darf, nicht geben kann auf Erden, oder wir w&amp;auml;ren schon im Paradies. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Es ist wirklich unglaublich, so ein Bild im Hosensack zu tragen, ohne da&amp;szlig; es sich abnutzt, und dabei immer besser wird. Ab und zu f&amp;uuml;hlt man danach, zieht es aus der Tasche oder dem Portemonnaie und betrachtet es, na&amp;szlig; in str&amp;ouml;mendem Regen oder im Bad unter Wasser, im Wasserglas oder in der Sonne, oder es blitzt, wenn man es im Kerzenlicht hin- und herdreht.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Und wenn es Nacht ist, ertastet man die Formen mit den Fingern. Im Bett nachts unter der Decke, wenn man einsam ist oder wenn man krank im Spitalbett zwischen sterilen W&amp;auml;nden liegt, oder wenn man alleine stirbt, glaube ich, ist es sch&amp;ouml;n, so etwas in H&amp;auml;nden zu haben. Man kann sich daran w&amp;auml;rmen wie an einem hei&amp;szlig;en Stein. Oder k&amp;uuml;hlen wie an einem Schneekristall oder einem St&amp;uuml;ck aus blauem Eis. Man kann es ins Feuer legen oder ins Wasser.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Alle meine Welten sind hier konzentriert und schemenhaft zugleich vertreten, so wie eine Wiedergeburt, eine Wiederauferstehung in einer neuen Dimension.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Es ist so etwas wie Eintrittsgeld ins Paradies.&lt;/p&gt;', text_occasion_en-'&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; font-family: &#039;Times New Roman&#039;;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; font-family: &#039;Times New Roman&#039;;&quot;&gt;Written in Kaurinui on &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 12pt; font-family: &#039;Times New Roman&#039;;&quot;&gt;1 October 1978 &lt;/span&gt;on occasion of his designs for coins.&lt;/span&gt;', text_occasion_ge-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Verfa&amp;szlig;t anl&amp;auml;&amp;szlig;lich der Entw&amp;uuml;rfe f&amp;uuml;r M&amp;uuml;nzen 1978.&lt;/p&gt;', text_published_en-'&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Hundertwasser Coin catalogue, Gruener Janura AG: Glarus/Switzerland, 1978, pp. 3-6&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Schurian, Walter (ed.): Hundertwasser &amp;ndash; Sch&amp;ouml;ne Wege, Gedanken &amp;uuml;ber Kunst und Leben. (Beautiful Paths &amp;ndash; Thoughts on Art and Life) Deutscher Taschenbuch Verlag (dtv): Munich, 1983, pp. 80-82 and ed. 2004 (Langen M&amp;uuml;ller Verlag, Munich), pp. 97-98 (German)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Schmied, Wieland (ed.): Hundertwasser 1928&amp;ndash;2000, Catalogue Raisonn&amp;eacute;.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;&gt;Vol. II: F&amp;uuml;rst, Andrea Christa: Catalogue Raisonn&amp;eacute;. Taschen: Cologne, 2002, pp. 1022-1023 (German and English)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;', text_published_ge-'&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Katalog zu den Hundertwasser M&amp;uuml;nzen, Gruener Janura AG: Glarus/Schweiz, 1978, S. 10-15&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Schurian, Walter (Hg.): Hundertwasser &amp;ndash; Sch&amp;ouml;ne Wege, Gedanken &amp;uuml;ber Kunst und Leben. Deutscher Taschenbuch Verlag (dtv): M&amp;uuml;nchen 1983, S. 80-82 und Ausgabe 2004 (Langen M&amp;uuml;ller Verlag, M&amp;uuml;nchen), S. 97-98&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Schmied, Wieland (Hg.): Hundertwasser 1928&amp;ndash;2000, Catalogue Raisonn&amp;eacute; / Werkverzeichnis.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Vol. II: F&amp;uuml;rst, Andrea Christa: Catalogue Raisonn&amp;eacute; / Werkverzeichnis. Taschen: K&amp;ouml;ln 2002, S. 1022-1023 (Deutsch und Englisch)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;', text_author-'Hundertwasser', text_orig_lang-'', text_translator-'', text_source_en-'', text_source_ge-'', text_excerpt-'', text_origin-'']

